The longer the index finger than the ring finger indicates the lower risk cancer
The men who have the index finger longer than the ring finger, they are exposed to less risk that gets the prostate cancer.
It is surprising conclusion of the study, which was published in the center of the british magazine cancer.
It may be related to the surface of the male hormone testosterone.
`` Our results show that the relative length finger can serve as a simple test of the risk of prostate cancer, in particular for men to 60 years, "said the co - author of study Ros Eelesová, Professor Cancer Institute at the University of Warwick University.
The finger might help determine who men should take the test for prostate cancer, especially in combination with a genetic risk threatening or other factors, such as the family health burden, she added Eelesová.
In the period 1994 - 2009 watched with colleagues in Britain, more than 1500 prostate cancer patients and in parallel over three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the members of the study should index finger on the right hand of less than the ring finger.
Paid for them as likely prostate cancer as for 19% of those whose fingers were as long.
In the case of those who had the index finger longer than the ring finger, however, this risk declined by 33%, for a man in his late fifties, the decline in even 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of these two fingers - shaped by prenatal processes - perhaps reflects the different levels, which is a child issued in the womb.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index finger.
Early studies have shown that just testosterone supports the growing prostate cancer.
The leading czech geneticist and a former President of the Academy of Sciences of Professor Václav Pačes for ČTK he said that on this study, he knows, but is he says that the relationship between the length of his fingers and cancer was `` entirely proven ."
