The normal practice of democracy
Support for democracy in Latin America is rising, as well as support for the private business.
Crime is greater than the concerns of unemployment.
And Brazil, many of the regions considers it 's more powerful than the United States.
There are some of the results of the survey Latinobarómetro, which took place in the 18 countries, and walked exclusively in the Economist magazine.
Since the survey held since 1995, may i to follow the change in attitude across the entire area.
In this year 's survey, which took place in September and at the beginning of October, dominated by two related things.
The first is that Latin America is fairly cheerful mood.
The second is to improve the stability of the attitudes toward democracy and its key institutions.
Support for democracy in several countries on the edge of the Pacific in South America has significantly increased (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where is from the year 2002 economic growth on average 6% per year, increased support for democracy from a minimum of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
Increased also in Mexico, where the economics of recovering from a deep decline in production in the last year.
But only about half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, two of the most populated areas, are convinced democrats, which is the regional average (see Figure 2).
About 44% of respondents across the entire area gives satisfaction with it, as in their country of democracy works in practice, this is the same number as the last year, but compared to 2001, when it was about 25%, this is a big increase (Figure 3).
About $34% said that they have confidence in the Vedek in his country and 45% of trust in the government, once again, this is the same number as in the past year, but it is a big difference compared to 2003 (17% and 24%).
Ten years ago has undermined democracy in Latin America, the economic crisis.
The aid during the global financial crisis is likely to be on the grounds that many latin american countries suffered only a recession, and with a strong recovery.
In addition, the stronger network of social security would help protect the poor people.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America this week announced that the ratio of latinoameričanů living in poverty has increased in 2009 only slightly and in this year again fell to 32%).
But the mood is amended in a broad range from country to country (see Figure 4).
Strong economic performance Brazil and its popularity of outgoing President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, is reflected in the widely accepted sense of progress.
This situation is rare in Mexico and Central America, where there was a recession worse and worse, the violent crime.
