The planned mosque in Temecule receives approval of the Planning Commission
The planned mosque in Temecule gained unanimous support local Planning Commission after more than five hours often passionate public testimony.
Critics of the project, that the sponsoring terrorism, and will lead to suspension of trade.
However, the jury decided on Wednesday night, that the new religious center is in accordance with the local laws and will be aesthetically impressive.
`` Many good people came to support this project - christians, the Jews, you name it, "said the snakes Nael, President of the Islamic Center in Temecula Valley, on Thursday morning.
`` I am on it as an american citizen very proud. "
`` It smacks of justice always wins. "
`` The opposition 's minimum, "he added.
`` Those who are against only shout loudly. "
`` We have in our valley really good people. "
Negotiations began in six hours of the night, and it took nearly midnight, when most of the time worked discussion with people who were for or against the center. these voices were evenly divided, is the Press - enterprise.
The discussion continued on the internet pages of newspapers.
`` It does not exist anymore, America, "appeared one comment.
`` We are the planet of the Apes the Statue of Liberty in the sand. "
`` America has fallen. "
The planned Islamic Center triggered protests also in other parts of the country, including the Ground Zero, the scene of the tragedy, which took place on September 11,2001, when the New York attacked the terrorists.
In the Valley Temecula the Imam Mahmoud Harmoush violence condemned.
His religious community of approximately 135 families plagued with at Riverside County for years without incident, but he wished more and more space than inventory of space, who rented together with the manufacturer of filtering systems.
The new mosque of dimensions 24 943 square feet in the Mediterranean style architecture, too, will have two minarets and grow up to a height of 43 feet.
It should take place of 4,32 acres of Nicolas Road, about three miles east of Chaparral High School.
Opponents are still on the project can still appeal to the City Council.
Microbes with resistance to arsenic increases the possibility of new types of life on Earth or elsewhere.
The discovery of the strange bacteria, which can use arsenic as one of their nutrients, extends the scope for the search for new forms of life on Earth, and perhaps even further.
Researchers discovered unusual bacteria here on Earth, and argue that this is a sign that life has options outside the main elements which have been considered and basic.
`` This organism is twofold ability. "
`` Can growth, either because of phosphorus or arsenic. "
`` This is a very special, but it 's not evidence that this is a form of a truly' extraterrestrial life ', "commented this fact Paul C. W. Davies of Arizona State University, co - author of the report, which have appeared on Thursday in online magazine Science.
For a long time, it was considered necessary for the life of the main elements of the six - carbon, nitrogen, hydrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulphur.
However, scientists have found that bacteria, discovered in mono Lake in California, they are able to continue to growth, after the for arsenic will replace the phosphorus.
`` You wonder what it is still possible, "said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, co - author of messages.
This finding is significant for searching for life outside the country, because researchers must be able to detect life and you know how life can look, said Anbar.
The study focuses on the microbes found on Earth.
However, the report on this innovation, published in order to about her discussed, which betrayed the details of the discovery, aroused widespread speculation on the Internet, that the report reveals the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
It 's not so.
The discovery of the `` shows that other planetary organisms may be able to take advantage of the other elements that drive biochemistry and that a set of elements, which are considered 'standard', may not be for life so absolutely necessary, "said Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, the Open University, in Milton Keynes, United Kingdom.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
`` This work is unusual, because it shows the replacement of one element of other in basic biochemistry and biochemical patterns, "he added Cockell.
It was not accidental discovery.
Felisa wolf - Simon from Astrobiologického Institute for NASA, which led the study, focused on Mono Lake, because it shows a high level of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically very similar elements, she thought, therefore, that the microbe, which is exposed to the two elements, may be able to replace the one behind the other.
`` Arsenic is poisonous mainly because its chemical behavior is very similar to the phosphorus. "
`` The result is that the organisms can be difficult to these elements separated. "
`` However, arsenic is so different that, as well as Phosphorus does not work if they get into the body, starts to work in the biochemical processes, "explained Anbar.
Scientists collected bacteria known as GFAJ - 1 and issue is the growing arsenic concentration, which are bacteria able to adapt and growth.
Microbes are better when the phosphorus, but, given that can survive also with refund arzenem, increases the possibility that a form of life, which makes use of arsenic, it may occur naturally, either elsewhere on the ground, or on another planet or months, where is arsenic more common.
Jamie S. Foster, assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, he said that the idea of arsenic, which could be replaced by the phosphorus, it is not new, but never found an example, on which this fact.
Arsenic was more common in earlier times on the ground, she said, and so scientists have speculated that it may benefit from the previous life forms.
`` This suggests that could be different ways to create life, not only in a manner, which was created in the early period of the country, "said Foster, which was part of the research team wolf - Simon.
Research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institutes of Health
