The United States amending the rules for the granting of visas
People will have to call on the services of the Centre for visa applicants even before the interview on the consular department; costs will be lower and reduced to the waiting period.
Of 10 January 2011 will change the process of consultation visas at the embassies and consulates of the United States.
With a new procedure will have to most applicants turn to the center of services for visa applicants (from English Vladimír) even before the interview on the consular department.
The staff of Vladimír removes biometric information of the applicant, and you will be evaluated before the interview consular department.
The new procedure will have a certain advantage, which is calculated the following:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, there will be no need to pay a fee for the agreement between the meeting, the other for the processing of applications and another for the delivery of the document the transport service.
The applicant shall pay only one fee, which will cover all three services.
The current fare will remain unchanged: the amount corresponding to $140 a tourist visa, 150 dollars for cases of visa applications (including visas for temporary workers) and 390 dollars for a visa for traders and investors.
People who want to restore their visa, they will not have to go through an interview with the consular officer, but only to turn to the nearest Vladimír, where will submit its documents and removed the fingerprints.
Whereas the biometric information will be removed in Vladimír, applicants who will require a second meeting with the conversation at the consular department, here they spend less time than in the past.
Similarly, those who will apply for a visa at the consulate in Ciudad Juarez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer be an extra pay the fee for the $26.
For more information about a new procedure in the visa application visit the following Web page http: / / mexico. usembassy. / gov boletines / _ sp 101201 Visas - FAQS. html
NASA shall notify the discovery of extraterrestrial life
America 's Space Agency convened on tomorrow press conference to present a discovery that could cause a breakthrough in search of extraterrestrial life.
The National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA), the United States shall notify tomorrow, Thursday, astrobiologický discovery, which could confirm the theory of the existence of extraterrestrial life.
The discovery of tomorrow will be presented in 13 hours of experts on astrobiologii, science, which is the study of origin, the evolution of, and the spread of the future life in the universe, at a press conference at the headquarters of the NASA in Washington, D. C.
When she invited journalists, NASA assured that will be `` discovery, which will break in search of extraterrestrial life, "which roused speculation experts from other countries.
The discovery could confirm the theory that there are, in addition to us and other creatures, living in the inhospitable conditions, which were considered uninhabitable, and who could provide the possibility that one day become intelligent creatures, as there are people, if we are to improve the conditions in which they live.
According to the appearance of a microbe, which was found at the bottom of the lake mono in Yosemistkém National Park, Calif., where he lives in the environment, which was deemed too poisonous for any form of life, as the lake is rich in arsenic.
The creature somehow arsenic used to his life, and that its ability to increases the likelihood that a similar life would be on other planets, which do not have the atmosphere, what is on the ground.
According to the astrobiologů, if these organisms used in its metabolism of arsenic, will demonstrate that, `` there is another, the second form of life, different from the one we know. "
The Space Agency shall notify the thing discoveries for tomorrow 's press conference.
The conference will participate in geobioložka Pamela Conrad, which is studying the possibility that the existence of life on Mars; biologist Steven Benner, one of the scientists who studied the Titan (the largest moon of Saturn) with the prospect that its chemical composition is similar to that on Earth.
